1 Introduction

This .html file is a brief demonstration of the previous work of Zhi Wang, Shang-Jin Wei, Xinding Yu, Kunfu Zhu entitled Measures of Participation in Global Value Chains and Global Business Cycles. WIOD Data, 2016 Release (see http://www.wiod.org/release16) is used in R studio.

2 Cross-sectional decomposition using the data of 2000

2.1 Include dataset & packages

## Dataset
chr1 = "WIOT"
chr2 = "_October16_ROW.RData"
datatemp = paste(chr1,2000:2014,chr2,sep = "")
temploop = 1
load(datatemp[temploop])
N <- 44;
n <- 56;

This chunk is a preparation for the below loop that conduct decomposition for the 10 years series of data.

## Pakages
library(Matrix)
library(ggplot2)
library(abind)
library(dplyr)
library(reshape2)
library(plm)

Packages used in this file are Matrix, ggplot2, abind. Matrix is used for dgCMatrix-class and large block matrices. ggplot2 is for the data visualization. And abind allows to concatenate matrices in to multidimensional arrays unlimitedly.

2.2 Calculate basic matrices

## Calculate Coefficient Matrix A for Intermediate Production
X <- wiot[wiot$IndustryCode=="GO",]
X <- X[, seq(1,N*n)+5]
Z <- data.matrix(wiot[seq(1,N*n), seq(1,N*n)+5])
A <- Z/kronecker(matrix(1,N*n,1), t(as.numeric(X)))
A[is.nan(A)] <- 0
A <- as(A, "dgCMatrix")

## Decompose the A Matrix into Ad (Domestic) and Af (Foreign)
A_diag <- replicate(N, kronecker(matrix(1,n,n), 1), simplify=FALSE)
AA_diag <- bdiag(A_diag)
Ad <- AA_diag * A
Af <- as(as.matrix(A - Ad), "dgCMatrix")

## Calculate Coefficient Vector V for Value-Added Entries
Va <- X - apply(Z, 2, sum)
V <- Va / X
V[is.nan(as.matrix(V))] <- 0

## Generate the Diagnal of V: Vhat
Vhat <- Diagonal(N*n,x = as.numeric(V))

## Calculate Final Consumption Matrix Y, (Ylist in the Code)
Ypart <- data.matrix(wiot[seq(1, N*n), seq(N*n+1, N*n+N*5) + 5])
Ylist <- c()
for(i in 1:N){Ylist<-cbind(Ylist, apply(Ypart[, seq(i*5-4,i*5)], 1, sum))}

## Decompose the Matrix Y into Yd (Domestic) and Yf (Foreign)
Ylist1 <- kronecker(matrix(1, N*n, N), 0)
for(i in 1:N){Ylist1[seq((i-1)*n+1, i*n), i]<-Ylist[seq((i-1)*n+1, i*n), i]}
Ylist2 <- Ylist-Ylist1

## Generate the Diagnal of Yd, Yf and Y: Ydhat and Yfhat
Yhat <- Diagonal(N*n,apply(Ylist, 1, sum))
Ydhat <- Diagonal(N*n,apply(Ylist1, 1, sum))
Yfhat <- Diagonal(N*n,apply(Ylist2, 1, sum))
rm(Ylist, Ylist1, Ylist2, Ypart, A_diag, AA_diag, Z, X, V)

For detailed demonstration of this methodology, please refer to the paper (http://www.nber.org/papers/w23222.pdf).

2.3 Decomposition of value added and final consumption

B <- solve(Diagonal(N*n)-A)
L <- solve(Diagonal(N*n)-Ad)
VBY <- as.matrix(Vhat%*%B%*%Yhat)
V_D <- as.matrix(Vhat%*%L%*%Ydhat)
V_R <- as.matrix(Vhat%*%L%*%Yfhat)
V_GVC_S <- as.matrix(Vhat%*%L%*%Af%*%L%*%Ydhat)
V_GVC_C <- as.matrix(Vhat%*%L%*%Af%*%(B%*%Yhat-L%*%Ydhat))

Again, refer to the paper for demonstration.

2.4 Backward linkage and forward linkage

B_link <- matrix(apply(V_GVC_S+V_GVC_C, 2, sum)/apply(VBY, 2, sum), nrow = n, ncol = N)
F_link <- matrix(apply(V_GVC_S+V_GVC_C, 1, sum)/apply(VBY, 1, sum), nrow = n, ncol = N)
  • Forward Industrial Linkage measures domestic value added generated from GVCs production and trade activities as a share of total sector value added (GDP);
  • Backward Industrial Linkage measures the percentage of a countrys final goods production contributed by both domestic and foreign factors that involve cross country production sharing activities.
## A Brief Look at Mining Sector
qplot(B_link[4,], F_link[4,], xlim = c(0,1), ylim = c(0,1), xlab = "Backward linkage", ylab = "Forward linkage", main = "Backward and Forward linkage (Mining in 2000)") + geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)

Apart from sector-wise perspective, we can also have a look at the country-wise situation where country is held fixed.

## A Brief Look at Australia
qplot(B_link[,1], F_link[,1], xlim = c(0,1), ylim = c(0,1), xlab = "Backward linkage", ylab = "Forward linkage", main = "Backward and Forward linkage (Australia in 2000)") + geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)

### Finish Decomposition with Time Series Data

The output contains four 3-Dimensional arrays, each representing V_D, V_R, V_GVC_C, V_GVC_S respectively, consisting data covering 15 years, 44 regions and 56 sectors. Now we can use these data for further econometrical analysis.

3.2 Linkage variation along with the time

load("decomposition.Rdata")
decomposition <- decomposition %>%
  mutate(fl=(fs+fc)/fv) %>%
  mutate(bl=(bs+bc)/bv)
fl_matrix <- matrix(data = decomposition$fl, nrow = 15, ncol = N*n, byrow = TRUE)
bl_matrix <- matrix(data = decomposition$bl, nrow = 15, ncol = N*n, byrow = TRUE)
sampleplot <- cbind(Year=2000:2014,CHN_Mining = fl_matrix[,396],RUS_Mining = fl_matrix[,2020],USA_Mining = fl_matrix[,2356],JPN_Mining = fl_matrix[,1348])
sampleplot <- melt(data.frame(sampleplot), "Year")
qplot(Year, value, data = sampleplot, geom = c("path","point"), colour = variable, ylim = c(0,1), xlab = "Year", ylab = "Forward linkage", main = "Forward Linkage of Country-sectors Changing over Time")

By grouping different sorts of value added, and analysing jointly, we can plot the trend of proportion of different sorts of value added changing over time.

grp_res <- decomposition %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(Domestic = sum(fd)/sum(fv), Trdtnal.Trd = sum(fr)/sum(fv), GVC_S = sum(fs)/sum(fv), GVC_C = sum(fc)/sum(fv))
grp_res<-melt(grp_res, "Year")
ggplot(grp_res, ylab = "Forward linkage") +
  geom_line(aes(x = Year, y = value, colour = variable)) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = Year, y = value, colour = variable)) +
  facet_grid(variable ~ ., scales = 'free_y')
